1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 {Together with 2...d5, this is Black's main answer to the
Alapin Variation. After 2...Nf6 we find a large number of lines that Black can
choose from. Very rich positions are reached with a wide variety of centre
types. Sometimes White has a hard time claiming an advantage, but Black has to
overcome many practical problems and play very precisely.} (2... e6 3. Nf3 d5
4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 {Transposing to a position from the Tarrasch Variation of
the French defence in which White has played c2-c3.} Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 {In
Chapter V, the different deviations are analysed.} (6... Nf6 {Positions of
this type in which Black plays Nf6 are the subject of Chapter VI.}) 7. dxc5
Bxc5 8. O-O Nge7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nb3 Bd6 {The mainline is examined in Chapter
VIII.} (10... Bb6 {And its main alternative is found in Chapter VII.})) 3. e5
Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 (4... e6 {This has been one of the mainlines in the Alapin
Variation for many years.} 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {Alongside with some rare
moves, this is analysed in Chapter I.} (6... b6 {As an important secondary
line with its own characteristics, this the subject of Chapter II.}) 7. Bc4 Nc6
8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 {This position is studied exhaustively in Chapters III and
IV.} O-O 10. Rd1) (4... d6 5. Na3 {This atypical development, which is a
specialty of Sergei Tiviakov, is covered in Chapter IX.}) 5. Bc4 Nb6 {One of
the main options for the second player. It offers abundant chances for both
sides to create imbalances.} 6. Bb3 d5 (6... g6 {A minor line that does not
cause any inconveniences for White. It is the subject of Chapter XI.}) (6... e6
{A rare alternative with ideas similar to 4...e6, this is covered in Chapter X.
}) (6... d6 {Another rare move which is the subject of Chapter XIII.}) (6... c4
{A sharp line where White sacrifices a pawn to fight for the initiative. It is
analysed in Chapter XII.}) 7. exd6 c4 (7... Qxd6 {Black does not advance c5-c4.
This is covered in Chapter XIV.}) 8. Bc2 Qxd6 {Entering the mainline and
reaching very complex positions. It is the subject of Chapter XV.} *

