1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 e6 {An elastic pawn advance that was very
popular in the 2000-2010 decade.} 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 {The main idea of
Black's fourth move. Black undermines White's pawn centre and doesn't show his
cards yet regarding his piece development, giving rise to a position with a
tense centre, very rich in content. Many strong players have been playing this
scheme against the Alapin Variation with Black.} (6... Be7 7. Bc4 d6 8. O-O Bd7
{Sometimes the second player performs the manoeuvre Bd7-c6, developing his
knight to d7 later. The bishop does a good job on c6 and its square hasn't
been weakened by the pawn move b6. At the same time, the knight controls e5
and has the potential to be further developed to c5 later.} (8... O-O 9. Qe2 {
transposes to Chapter III.}) 9. exd6 $1 {A good central reaction, trying to
misplace the black bishop on d7.} Bxd6 10. Nc3 (10. Bxd5 exd5 11. Re1+ Be7 ({
To a balanced game leads} 11... Be6 12. Ng5 O-O 13. Qd3 g6 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15.
Nd2 Qh4 $13 {[%csl Rf2,Rh2]}) 12. Qb3 O-O 13. Qxb7 Nc6 14. Nc3 Rb8 15. Qa6 $14
{1-0 (28) Stevic,H (2530) -Jankovic,A (2273) Bizovac 2002}) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3
Qc7 12. Bd3 {Leading to a game with delayed hanging pawns for White, which is
very common in the Alapin Variation.} Bc6 (12... Qxc3 $2 {This ambitious
capture of the pawn is a mistake, but it forces White to play with maximum
precision.} 13. d5 $3 {A surprising second pawn sacrifice, ignoring the threat
against the rook.} Qxa1 {The capture of the rook is the best way to put
White's play in question. Alternatives offer an excellent dynamic game for the
first player without any major concessions.} (13... exd5 14. Re1+ Kd8 (14...
Be6 15. Ng5 Bb4 (15... Qxa1 $4 16. Nxe6 $18) 16. Nxe6 Qxe1+ 17. Qxe1 Bxe1 18.
Nc7+ Kd8 19. Nxa8 Bc3 20. Rb1 $16 {It is not clear how Black is going to
capture the knight on a8}) 15. Rb1 Re8 16. Rxe8+ Bxe8 17. Bb2 $16 {[%csl Rd8,
Rf6,Rg7] With an excellent piece placement for White.}) (13... O-O 14. dxe6
Bxe6 (14... h6 {Avoiding topics with Bxh7+.} 15. exf7+ $1 Rxf7 16. Rb1 Qc7 17.
Qb3 $18 {[%csl Rf7,Rg8][%cal Gc1b2,Gd3g6] Black's lack of development will be
fatal.}) 15. Ng5 g6 (15... Qxa1 $4 16. Bxh7+ Kh8 17. Qh5 $18) 16. Rb1 {[%csl
Rb7][%cal Gc1b2,Gb1b7]} Qf6 17. Be4 {[%csl Rb7,Rd6][%cal Gd1d6] Black is
unable to contain the threats of his opponent.}) 14. Qb3 {[%csl Ra8][%cal
Gc1b2,Gb3b7]} Be5 {[%cal Rc1b2]} (14... Na6 15. Ba3 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Gf1a1]}
Qxf1+ 16. Bxf1 Bxa3 17. Qxa3 {[%cal Re8g8,Rh8f8,Gf3e5,Gf1a6]} Nc7 18. Qc3 {
[%csl Rc7,Rg7][%cal Gc3c7,Gc3g7]} Nxd5 19. Qxg7 $16 {The exposed situation of
the black king offers an advantage for the first player.}) ({A serious error is
} 14... Qf6 $4 15. Bg5 $18) (14... O-O $2 15. Bb2 $16 {White recovers the
material while keeping the initiative.}) 15. Qxb7 O-O (15... Qxa2 16. dxe6 Qxe6
17. Nxe5 O-O 18. Qe4 $1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Ge4h7] White wisely chooses to
