Be7 9. Qe2 O-O 10. Rd1 {This is considered the main move and my proposal after
carefully analysing the numerous alternatives. It is necessary to highlight
the large number of possibilities for both sides at each move, arriving on
many occasions at very similar positions. Although this is meant to be a
theoretical work, I recommend studying the typical manoeuvres and the frequent
tactical themes that this line offers. In this position, the second player has
a large number of answers.} Na5 (10... Bd7 {With the simple idea of speeding
up the development of pieces on the queenside.} 11. Bd2 Rc8 (11... Ndb4 {
[%cal Gd6d5,Gc6a5] Threatening d6-d5, followed by Na5, and the exchange of
White's powerful light-squared bishop.} 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. Nc3 {We are in an
isolated pawn position where the pieces of both sides are not in their optimal
location.} Ne7 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gb4d5,Ge7f5,Ge7g6] A logical move, trying to
regroup the pieces. Another critical moment for White. He must choose between
two moves that lead to situations of a different nature.} ({Another option is} 
13... Na5 14. Ne4 Bc6 ({A serious mistake is} 14... Nxc4 $4 15. Qxc4 {[%cal
Ge4d6,Gd2b4] , gaining material.}) 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. a3 Bxf3 {The only move to
avoid a clear disadvantage.} 17. Qxf3 Nbc6 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4][%cal Gc6d4,Ga5c4]}
18. Bxa5 Nxa5 19. Ba2 Qb6 20. b4 Nc6 21. d5 exd5 22. Rxd5 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rf7]
The bishop is superior to the knight in this type of position.}) 14. Bg5 {
The safest way, limiting the opponent's options.} ({The most ambitious
continuation, but also one that offers more possibilities for Black is} 14. Ng5
$5 Qc7 {[%csl Yh2][%cal Gd6h2]} 15. a3 Nbd5 ({It is somewhat naive to capture
the h2-pawn with} 15... Bxh2+ $2 16. Kh1 Nbd5 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 exd5 19.
Qd3 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gd3h7]} g6 20. Rac1 Qb8 21. g3 $16) 16. Rac1 Nf4 17. Qe4 {
[%csl Rh7][%cal Ge4h7]} Neg6 18. Bb5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1c7]} f5 $1 {With each
