13... d5 14. Ne1 $1 {The same idea as in the previous game. White allows the
transfer of his rook to the kingside.} b6 $6 {This is a waste of time, since
the threat of 15...Ba6 is not real.} 15. Rh3 $16 {[%cal Ge2h5] The first
player begins to develop a dangerous initiative on the kingside, which gives
him the advantage.} g6 ({No better is} 15... f5 16. Qh5 h6 17. Rg3 $1 {
Strongest.} (17. Bxh6 Qe8 18. Qxe8 Rxe8 19. Rg3 $16) 17... f4 18. Rg4 Kh8 19.
Qg6 Rg8 20. Rxf4 $16 {[%cal Gf4f7] With a great white advantage.}) 16. Bh6 Re8
17. Qg4 ({Even more precise was} 17. Nf3 f6 18. Qd2 {[%cal Ge5f6,Gf3g5] With
the idea of 19.exf6 and 20.Ng5.} Nc4 19. Qc1 fxe5 20. dxe5 Qd7 21. b3 Na5 22.
Ng5 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gg5h7]} Bxg5 (22... Ba6 $4 23. Nxh7 Kxh7 24. Bg7+ {
And White is winning by checkmate.}) 23. Qxg5 Ba6 24. Rf3 Nc6 25. Qf4 Qe7 26.
h4 Rac8 27. h5 {[%csl Rg6] With a powerful white attack.}) 17... f5 (17... Ba6
18. Nf3 f5 19. Qf4 Qc7 20. Ng5 Bd8 21. Rg3 $16 {[%cal Gh2h5] With the idea of
breaking with h2-h4-h5 and attacking the black king.}) 18. Qf4 Nc6 19. Nf3 Ba6
20. Bg5 $2 {The correct square but the wrong piece.} ({Much better was} 20. Ng5
$1 Bxg5 (20... Nxd4 21. Nxh7 Be2 22. Qxd4 Bg4 23. Nf6+ Bxf6 24. exf6 {[%cal
Gf6f7,Gd4g7] Threatening 25.f7+ and 26.Qg7++.} e5 25. Qxd5+ Qxd5 26. Nxd5 Bxh3
27. Nc7 Bg4 28. Nxe8 Rxe8 29. Rc1 Rd8 30. f3 Bh5 31. Rc7 $18 {With a decisive
advantage for White.}) 21. Bxg5 Qc7 22. Bf6 Rf8 23. Qh6 Rac8 24. Rd1 {[%csl
Rd4][%cal Gd1d4] Defending the d4-pawn before the decisive offensive.} Rfe8 25.
Qg5 Rf8 26. Rh6 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh2h5] And White is very close to victory.})
20... Rc8 $2 {Wasting the opportunity.} ({Necessary was} 20... Nxd4 $1 21. Qxd4
Bxg5 22. Qa4 {[%cal Ga4a6,Ga4d7]} Bc4 23. Nxg5 Qxg5 24. b3 {[%csl Rc4]} b5 25.
Qa5 d4 26. bxc4 dxc3 27. Rxc3 bxc4 28. Rxc4 $14 {After the complications White
still has a slight advantage.}) 21. Qh4 $16 h5 22. Rg3 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gg3g6]}
Kf7 (22... Bxg5 23. Nxg5 Qe7 24. Qf4 Kg7 25. h4 Nd8 26. Nh3 Nf7 27. a4 $16 {
With a significant positional advantage.}) 23. Bxe7 ({Even stronger was} 23. b4
$1 Nxb4 ({Insufficient was} 23... Bxg5 24. Nxg5+ Kg7 25. b5 Nxd4 26. Qxd4 Rc4
27. Qd2 f4 28. Rd3 $18) 24. Bf6 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf3e5,Re7f6,Ge5f6] Taking
advantage of the fact that the black knight does not control the e5-square.}
Rg8 (24... Rf8 25. Rxg6 Ke8 26. Rg7 Nc6 27. Rc1 {Putting the last piece into
play and cutting off the black king's escape to the queenside.} Bc4 28. Nb5 $3
Bxb5 29. Bxe7 $18 Qxe7 30. Rxe7+ Nxe7 31. Rxc8+ Nxc8 32. Qxh5+ $18) 25. Ng5+
Ke8 26. Nxe6 Bxf6 27. exf6 Qd6 28. Re1 $18 {White enjoys a decisive advantage.}
) 23... Rxe7 (23... Qxe7 24. Qf4 Rg8 25. a4 Qb4 26. Ng5+ Ke7 27. Nh7 {[%cal
Gf4g5,Gh7f6] Threatening 28.Qg5+ and 29.Nf6+.} g5 {Black has nothing better.}
28. Nxg5 Qxd4 29. Nxe6 Qxe5 30. Re3 Qxf4 31. Nxd5+ Kf7 32. Ndxf4 $16 {With a
better endgame for White.}) 24. Qf6+ Ke8 25. Rxg6 $18 {White is winning.} Kd7
26. Nxd5 exd5 27. Qd6+ Ke8 28. Rg8+ Kf7 29. Qg6# 1-0

