11... d5 12. Bf4 Bd7 13. Nc3 Rc8 14. h4 $5 {An interesting pawn sacrifice.
This lateral pawn advance is thematic and often the pawn sacrifice is
justified. Another way to implement the plan is the preparatory g2-g3.} ({
More solid and probably better was} 14. Rac1 f6 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Bd6 Re8 17.
h3 $14 {Without hurry, White improves his position by controlling the critical
e5-square.}) 14... Bxh4 $1 {Black accepts the pawn sacrifice and sharpens the
game.} ({Also possible was the more cautious} 14... a6 15. g3 {[%cal Gg3h4]}
Qe8 16. Re1 h6 17. Rac1 f5 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. Bd6 $14 {[%csl Ge5]}) 15. g3 Be7
16. Kg2 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gd1h1] With the idea of moving his rooks to the
kingside and attacking the enemy king. Black has to act if he doesn't want to
run into insurmountable problems.} f5 $1 17. exf6 Bxf6 {White has compensation
for the pawn due to the h-file and the control of the e5-square. The position
is dynamically equal.} 18. Rh1 ({To an unclear game led} 18. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6]}
Be7 19. Rh1 Rxf4 $1 20. gxf4 Qf8 21. Bc2 Qxf4 22. Bxh7+ Kf8 23. Bd3 Bf6 $13)
18... g6 ({Worth consideration was} 18... Nxd4 $5 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. Qd3 Rxf4
21. Qxh7+ Kf8 22. gxf4 Qf6 23. Rh4 Ke7 $13) 19. Rad1 Qe7 ({To an even game led
} 19... a6 20. Na4 Rf7 21. Nxb6 Qxb6 22. Ba4 Rcf8 23. Bxc6 Bxc6 24. Rd2 e5 25.
Nxe5 Bxe5 26. Qxe5 $11 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gb6d8] And the black weaknesses on the
dark squares cannot be exploited.}) 20. Rh6 (20. Nb5 $5) 20... Rf7 (20... a6 {
[%cal Rc3b5]} 21. Qd2 Rf7 22. Rdh1 Rcf8 {With a tense position where White has
compensation for the pawn and all three outcomes are possible.}) 21. Qe3 ({
Much better was} 21. Nb5 $1 Bg7 (21... e5 $5 22. dxe5 Nxe5 23. Bxe5 Bxe5 24.
Nxe5 Bxb5 25. Qe3 Rf5 $13) 22. Rh2 Nc4 23. Bxc4 Rxf4 24. gxf4 dxc4 25. Rdh1 Nb4
26. Nc3 Nd3 $13 {With a complex position that is difficult to evaluate.}) 21...
Na5 $6 ({Very strong was} 21... Qb4 $1 22. Qd3 (22. Ng5 Bxg5 23. Bxg5 a5 24. g4
Rcf8 25. f4 a4 26. Bc2 Nc4 $36 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3][%cal Gc4e3] And Black starts
having dangerous threats.}) 22... Rcf8 23. Ne2 Nc4 24. Qb1 Qb6 25. Kg1 a5 $36 {
Black takes over the initiative.}) 22. Rdh1 Nbc4 23. Qe2 b5 $2 {This is a
serious mistake that leads to a very difficult position.} (23... Nxb3 24. axb3
Nd6 25. Ne5 Rg7 26. g4 Nf7 27. R6h3 Nxe5 28. Bxe5 Rf7 29. Rf3 Bc6 $15 {White
has control of the e5-square but is over-extended and a pawn down.}) 24. Bc2
$16 b4 ({More tenacious was} 24... Rg7 25. b3 b4 26. bxc4 bxc3 27. Bxg6 $1 Rxg6
28. Rxh7 Bg7 29. Ne5 Be8 30. Nxg6 Bxg6 31. Bg5 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ge2e6]} Be4+
32. Qxe4 dxe4 33. Bxe7 Bxd4 34. R7h4 $16 {With a white advantage but some
technical problems left to solve.}) 25. Ne5 ({The direct} 25. Bxg6 {concluded
the game quickly.} hxg6 26. Ng5 Be8 27. Rxg6+ Rg7 28. Rgh6 Rg6 (28... Rxg5 29.
Bxg5 $18 {[%cal Gh6h8,Gg5e7]}) 29. Nxd5 $1 exd5 30. Rh8+ Bxh8 31. Qxe7 $18)
25... Bxe5 (25... Nxe5 26. dxe5 Bg5 27. Bxg5 Qxg5 28. Bxg6 $18) 26. Bxe5 Nxe5
27. Qxe5 Rg7 ({More resistance offered} 27... Qf6 28. Qxf6 Rxf6 29. Rxh7 Rf7
30. Bxg6 Rxh7 31. Bxh7+ Kf7 32. Ne2 $16) 28. Bxg6 hxg6 29. Qf4 1-0

