12. dxe5 Qc7 ({Another option was} 12... Na5 13. Bd3 Bd7 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Rab1
b5 16. a4 Nc4 17. Bf4 $14) 13. Bd3 ({Equally good was the always useful h-pawn
advance} 13. h4 $5) 13... O-O $6 {Castling is premature in this position and
offers White an advantage.} ({It was better to develop the queenside first.
Some possible variations are:} 13... Bd7 14. Rb1 Na5 15. h4 Bc6 16. Be3 Bd5 17.
Bb6 Qxc3 18. Rfc1 Qa3 19. Ng5 $44 {With an initiative for the sacrificed pawn.}
) (13... b6 14. Bf4 Bb7 15. Rad1 O-O 16. h4 Rfd8 17. h5 Na5 18. h6 g6 19. Ng5
Bd5 20. Rfe1 Qxc3 21. Be4 $44 {Looking for a way to take advantage of Black's
weaknesses on the kingside. White has full compensation for the pawn.}) 14. Re1
$16 b6 (14... g6 15. h4 b5 16. Bh6 Rd8 17. h5 {[%csl Rg6]} Bb7 18. Qe3 Rd7 19.
Be4 {The white queen is tied to the defence of the light-squared bishop. This
move works tactically. Also possible is 19.Bc2.} Nxe5 20. Bxb7 Nc4 21. Bxa8
Nxe3 22. Bxe3 $16 {With a material advantage.}) 15. Rb1 ({Much stronger was} 
15. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 (15... h6 16. Qe4 g6 17. Nxf7 Rxf7 18. Bxh6 Nxe5 19. Qxe5 Qxe5
20. Rxe5 Rh7 21. Bf4 $16) 16. Bxg5 Nxe5 {Entering a forced variation.} 17. Bf4
f6 18. Qe4 {[%csl Ra8,Rh7][%cal Ge4h7,Ge4a8]} g6 19. Qxa8 Bb7 20. Qa7 Ra8 21.
Bxe5 fxe5 22. Qxb7 Qxb7 23. Be4 Qb8 24. Bxa8 Qxa8 25. Rxe5 {Although good
technique is required, White has a very reasonable chances of winning the
endgame.}) 15... Bb7 ({Also valid is} 15... Rd8 16. h4 Bb7 17. Ng5 Bxg5 18.
Bxg5 Ne7 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Rxb6 Rd7 21. Qe3 Rad8 22. Bf1 Qxh4 23. Reb1 Qe7 24.
c4 $14) 16. Ng5 g6 $1 {The best defence.} (16... Bxg5 $6 17. Bxg5 Ne7 18. Rb4
$1 {An excellent and unusual transfer of the rook to the kingside.} Ng6 19. Rg4
$16 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] With a dangerous attack on the black king.}) 17. Nxh7
Rfd8 ({Much weaker was} 17... Nxe5 $2 18. Nxf8 Nxd3 19. Nxg6 Nxe1 20. Nxe7+
Qxe7 21. Qg4+ Kh7 22. Qh3+ Kg8 23. Qg3+ Kf8 24. Bh6+ Ke8 25. Rxe1 Rc8 26. h4 {
Bishops of different colours only increase White's advantage.}) 18. Nf6+ Kg7 $2
{After some excellent defensive moves Black makes a mistake that leads to a
lost position. This shows that beyond a certain objective equilibrium, the
play with the Black pieces is usually more difficult in practice.} ({Correct
was} 18... Bxf6 $1 19. exf6 Ne5 $1 ({An error is} 19... Qe5 $2 20. Rxb6 Rxd3
21. Qxe5 Nxe5 22. Rxb7 Nd7 23. Bg5 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4]}) 20. Bc2 Qxc3 21. Rb3 Qc4
22. Qxc4 Nxc4 23. Bh6 Rd5 $14 {And White has only a little plus.}) 19. Bf4 Na5
({Other variations also fail to offer a solution for Black:} 19... Rh8 20. Qg4
Rad8 21. Qg3 Na5 22. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5]} Qxc3 23. Red1 Nc6 24. Rbc1 Qb2
25. h5 $18) (19... Bc5 20. Rbd1 Ne7 21. Qg4 Rh8 22. Bg5 Kf8 23. Be4 Bxe4 24.
Qxe4 Rd8 25. Rxd8+ Qxd8 26. Qf4 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gg5d8]} Kg7 27. Ne4 Rh5 28. g4
$18) 20. Qg4 $18 Rh8 (20... Bc5 21. Rbd1 Rh8 22. Bxg6 fxg6 23. Rd7+ $18) 21.
Re3 Nc4 (21... Rag8 22. Rg3 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gd3g6]} Kf8 23. Nxg8 Rxg8 24. h4
Nc6 25. h5 $18 {[%csl Rg6]}) 22. Bxc4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc7c4,Gf4h6,Gg4c4]
Black resigned.} 1-0

