13. d4 Bg4 14. h3 ({An interesting choice is the direct} 14. Be4 {, leading to
more complex positions.} e5 (14... f5 $5 15. Bd3 Qc7 16. Be2 Rad8 17. Bd2 e5
18. Nb5 Qd7 19. Nxa7 e4 20. Nxc6 bxc6 21. Ne1 Bxe2 22. Qxe2 Qd5 23. Nc2 $14 {
[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc2b4,Ga1a6] White returns the extra pawn to activate his
pieces}) 15. Nb5 Qd7 16. dxe5 a6 17. Qxd7 Nxd7 18. Nd6 Nc5 19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. b4
$13 {With a complex middlegame without queens.}) 14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3 e5 16. Nb5
({Not enough for an advantage is} 16. Be4 f5 $1 17. Bxc6 Qxc6 18. Qxc6 bxc6 19.
Nc2 exd4 20. Nxd4 c5 21. Ne6 Bxc3 22. Ra6 Rfc8 23. Be3 $11) 16... Qd7 ({
Better was} 16... Qd5 17. Qxd5 Nxd5 18. Be4 a6 19. Bxd5 axb5 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21.
dxe5 Bxe5 $11) 17. Rd1 a6 ({Other possibilities are:} 17... exd4 {The most
solid choice.} 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. cxd4 Rfe8 20. Ra5 Qc6 21. Qxc6 bxc6 22. Kf1 {
The pair of bishops offers White practical chances in the endgame.}) (17...
Rfe8 18. Be3 exd4 19. Nxd4 Qd5 20. Qf4 Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Be5 22. Qh4 Bxd4 23. Rxd4
Qe5 24. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gc2][%cal Gc2e4,Ge4b7] The bishop can press on the
h1-a8 diagonal. White is slightly better.}) 18. d5 Nb4 (18... axb5 $6 19. dxc6
Qxc6 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Be4 Qc7 22. Be3 {[%csl Ge3,Ge4] White's bishop pair has
a lot of potential.}) 19. Na3 Nxc2 ({Much more precise was} 19... f5 $1 20.
cxb4 e4 21. Qe3 Nxd5 22. Qc5 Rfc8 $1 23. Rxd5 Qf7 24. Qd6 Bxa1 25. Rc5 b5 $1 {
[%csl Ra3,Rc2][%cal Ra3c4] The white minor pieces have difficulties in their
coordination.} 26. Rxc8+ Rxc8 27. Qxa6 Qd7 28. Be3 $13 {[%csl Ra3,Rc2] With an
unclear position.}) 20. Nxc2 Rac8 21. c4 f5 ({An interesting alternative was} 
21... e4 22. Qe3 Bxa1 23. Nxa1 Qd8 24. Nc2 Nd7 25. Bb2 Qb6 26. Qc3 f6 27. b4
Qd6 28. c5 $14 {[%cal Gc2e3]}) 22. Ba3 Rf7 23. Rac1 {The position is very
dynamic but White's play should arrive first.} Re8 ({Not a solution either was
} 23... Rd8 24. Qe2 Qe8 25. d6 Bh6 26. Ne3 Qe6 27. c5 Nd7 28. Rc4 $16) 24. c5
$16 e4 ({Worse was} 24... Nc8 25. c6 $1 bxc6 26. dxc6 $16) 25. Qe2 Nc8 26. Qc4
Na7 (26... Qb5 27. Nd4 Qxc4 28. bxc4 {[%csl Gd4]} Bxd4 29. Rxd4 g5 30. Rb1 Kg7
31. Rd2 Rd8 32. Re2 $16 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf2f3,Gg2g4] With the idea of
possible breaks with f2-f3 or g2-g4.}) 27. Nd4 f4 (27... Bxd4 28. Rxd4 $1 Nb5
29. Bb2 h6 {[%cal Gb5d4,Gg8h7] Capturing the rook was already possible.} 30.
Rd2 Kh7 31. b4 $16 {[%cal Gd5d6,Gc5c6] And the white central pawns were ready
to advance.}) 28. Ne6 ({More exact was} 28. c6 $1 bxc6 29. dxc6 Qc8 30. Ne2 $18
{[%cal Gd1d7]}) 28... Nb5 29. Bb4 e3 30. Ng5 ({Another path was} 30. fxe3 fxe3
31. Rf1 Bf6 32. Rf3 $16) 30... exf2+ 31. Kxf2 Qf5 32. Nxf7 Re4 33. c6 $1 {
White finishes off the game with strong moves, avoiding all the complications
presented by his opponent.} Kxf7 34. cxb7 Rxc4 35. bxc4 Qe5 36. cxb5 Qb2+ 37.
Kf1 Be5 38. d6 $18 f3 39. gxf3 Qb3 40. Ke2 Qe6 41. Rc7+ Kf6 42. b8=Q Bf4+ 43.
Kd3 Qd5+ 44. Kc2 Qa2+ 45. Kc3 Be5+ 46. Kd3 Qb3+ 47. Ke2 1-0

