15. d4 Qc7 (15... Rd8 16. Be3 Qc7 17. Rc1 Qa5 18. b4 Qh5 19. h3 $14 {White
adapts a typical type of structure with b3-b4, gaining space on the queenside.}
) 16. Re1 b5 {Black's counterplay consists of advancing his queenside pawns
while fighting against the white centre.} (16... Rd8 17. h3 b5 18. Be4 Be6 19.
Bg5 Bd5 20. Qd3 h6 21. Bh4 Qb7 22. Rac1 g5 23. Bg3 e6 24. c4 Bxe4 25. Qxe4 $14)
17. Bg5 ({An equivalent option was} 17. Be4 Bb7 18. Qd3 a6 19. h4 e5 20. d5
Rfd8 21. h5 $1 {Sacrificing a minor piece and demonstrating the tactical
potential of the white position.} f5 22. hxg6 fxe4 23. Qxe4 Na5 (23... Ne7 24.
gxh7+ Kh8 25. c4 $16 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc1b2,Gf3e5]}) 24. Rxa5 Bxd5 25. Qh4 hxg6
26. Ng5 Bf6 (26... Qxa5 27. Qh7+ Kf8 28. Qxg6 $40 {[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3f3,Gc1e3,
Ge3c5] With ideas like Re3-f3+ or Be3-c5+. The rook is well compensated and it
is Black who has problems to solve.}) 27. Ra3 $14 {The weak black king
guarantees White the better chances.}) 17... e6 18. Be4 $6 ({The right path was
} 18. Qd2 $1 Bb7 (18... a5 19. Bf4 Qd7 20. Bh6 Bxh6 21. Qxh6 {[%cal Gf3g5,
Gg5e4,Ge4c5]} f6 {Necessary to avoid 22.Ng5.} 22. Be4 Ra7 23. h4 Ne7 24. h5 Nf5
25. Qf4 $36 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Ga1d1,Gd4d5] The white pieces have objectives to
work on.}) 19. Bf4 {Dislodging the black queen.} Qd8 20. Bh6 {Exchanging the
defender of Black's king.} Ne7 21. Ne5 a5 22. h4 Rc8 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. h5 $36 {
[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3h3] And White has a dangerous initiative on the kingside.})
18... Bb7 19. Qd3 f5 $1 ({Another acceptable option is the typical break with} 
19... b4 {[%csl Rd4]} 20. h4 bxc3 21. Qxc3 h6 22. Be3 Qd7 23. Qd2 {[%csl Rh6]
[%cal Ge3h6]} Rfd8 24. Ra4 Kh7 25. h5 Ne7 26. hxg6+ Nxg6 $13 {With dynamic
balance.}) 20. Bxc6 Qxc6 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gb7g2] Black has intentionally
weakened his king to dominate the long diagonal.} 21. h4 ({Somewhat more
passive was} 21. b4 {Preventing the black breaks b4 and a5 at the cost of
giving all the light squares to his opponent.} f4 22. Be7 Rf5 23. Bc5 a6 24.
Qf1 $11) 21... a5 22. c4 (22. h5 $5 gxh5 23. Bf4 Rf7 24. c4 bxc4 25. bxc4 a4
26. Be5 {With a complex position and chances for both sides.}) 22... bxc4 ({
Somewhat imprecise was} 22... Qd6 $6 23. cxb5 Be4 24. Qe3 Qd5 25. Ne5 Qxb5 26.
Bh6 Ra7 27. Bxg7 Rxg7 28. Nc4 Bd5 29. Rxa5 $14) 23. bxc4 a4 24. c5 (24. Bf4
Rfc8 25. c5 Rd8 26. Be5 Bxe5 27. Rxe5 Qd7 28. Ree1 Bxf3 29. Qxf3 Qxd4 $11)
24... Qd5 25. Ra3 Bc6 $11 26. Qe3 Rfe8 27. Bh6 Bf6 28. Bg5 Bg7 29. Bh6 Bf6 30.
Bg5 Bg7 1/2-1/2

