15. d4 O-O 16. g3 {A correct idea, though rarely seen in this pawn structure.
White controls the f4-square but weakens the light squares around his king.}
Nh5 17. Re1 ({An interesting alternative was} 17. Bd2 $5 {[%csl Gc3][%cal
Gd2c3,Gd4d5] Defending the c3-pawn to start advancing the central mass of
pawns.} Nf6 18. d5 Ne5 19. Nxe5 Qxe5 20. c4 Ne4 21. Bxe4 Qxe4 22. Rc1 $14 {
[%cal Gf1e1,Gd2c3]}) 17... Rd8 18. Qe2 ({A line where the richness of ideas in
this structure is demonstrated starts with} 18. b4 $5 Nf6 19. Ng5 {[%cal Gd1f3]
} a6 20. Qf3 h6 21. Ne4 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf3][%cal Ge4b7]} e5 23. Nd5
Qd6 24. b5 $1 f5 25. Bb1 {[%cal Gb1a2,Rd6d5]} Be6 26. Nf4 $13 {With a very
sharp game that is difficult to evaluate.}) 18... Nf6 19. Bb2 ({A slight white
advantage could have been achieved by} 19. b4 b6 (19... a6 20. b5 Na5 21. bxa6
Nc6 22. Qc4 Be6 23. Qc5 Rxa6 24. Rxa6 bxa6 25. Ng5 Bd7 26. Nc4 $14 {[%cal
Gg5e4,Gc1f4]}) 20. Bb3 e6 21. Nc4 Nd5 22. Bd2 Bb7 23. b5 Nce7 24. Rac1 a6 25.
Nce5 $14 {White has a little plus in his favour.}) 19... e6 (19... e5 $1 {
This accurate central blow would have equalized the game. A possible
continuation is} 20. dxe5 Nxe5 21. Nxe5 Qxe5 22. Ra2 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Ga2b2,
Gc3c4]} Qc7 23. c4 Re8 24. Bd3 Qc6 25. Qd1 Bh3 26. Bxf6 Bxf6 27. Bf1 Bxf1 28.
Rxf1 Kg7 29. Nd5 a6 $11 {[%cal Gb7b5] The well-placed white knight has no
great influence on the position.}) 20. c4 ({The best chances of an advantage
offered} 20. Bd3 $5 a5 21. b4 e5 22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. dxe5 Qxe5 24. c4 Qc7 25. Ra3
Be6 26. Rea1 b6 27. c5 $14 {[%cal Gb6c5,Gb4a5] With a little pressure from
White.}) 20... Nb4 $11 {Black has equalized the game.} ({Also possible was} 
20... b6 21. d5 Nb4 22. dxe6 Bxe6 23. Bc3 a5 24. Ng5 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c6]})
21. Bb1 b6 22. Ba3 (22. Ng5 $5) 22... Bf8 ({The knight retreat} 22... Nc6 $5 {
[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6d4] was worthy of consideration.} 23. Rd1 Bb7 24. Ra2 Na5 {
[%csl Rb3][%cal Ga5b3] White's pawn structure is somewhat weak.} 25. Rc2 Ne4 (
25... Nxb3 $5 26. Ba2 Qc6 27. d5 Qa4 28. Be7 {With a very complex game.}) 26.
b4 Nb3 27. d5 {A necessary reaction against the active black knights.} a5 28.
bxa5 bxa5 $13 {The game is very sharp, but the black position is easier to
play.}) 23. Bb2 Bb7 24. d5 Bg7 25. Be5 $2 ({It was time to think about
equality. There were at least two acceptable paths:} 25. dxe6 fxe6 26. Ng5 Re8
27. h3 a5 28. Ng4 Nxg4 29. hxg4 Bxb2 30. Qxb2 Rad8 31. Qf6 Qg7 32. Qxg7+ Kxg7
33. Kf1 e5 $11 {The endgame is level, although there is some play left.}) (25.
Ng5 exd5 26. Nf5 $5 {A piece sacrifice leading to a forced draw.} gxf5 27. Bxf6
Bxf6 28. Qh5 Re8 29. Bxf5 dxc4 30. Qxh7+ Kf8 31. Qh6+ Bg7 32. Nh7+ Kg8 33. Nf6+
Bxf6 34. Bh7+ Kh8 35. Bg6+ $11) 25... Qe7 26. Qb2 (26. Nd4 Nfxd5 27. Bxg7 Nxe3
28. Bh6 Rxd4 29. Qxe3 Qd6 30. f3 Nd3 $36 {Black is in central control and
making progress.}) 26... exd5 27. cxd5 Nbxd5 $17 28. Nc4 Qf8 29. Ng5 Ng4 30.
Bxg7 Qxg7 31. Qxg7+ Kxg7 {With a clear extra pawn for Black that was converted.
} 32. h3 Ngf6 33. Ne5 Rf8 34. Bd3 Nb4 35. Rad1 Nxd3 36. Rxd3 Bd5 0-1

