{How should White play to get an advantage?} 1. d5 $1 {[%csl Re8]} e5 ({
The two captures on d5 are inferior:} 1... Nxd5 2. Ba4+ Ke7 3. Qf3 {White
already has enough compensation with his pair of bishops and the black king in
the centre. However, Black has a hard time getting his kingside pieces into
play, which gives White an advantage.} Rd8 4. Re1 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] A sad move,
but Black has nothing better.} 5. Bg5+ f6 6. Bxf6+ $1 Nxf6 7. Bb3 {[%csl Re6]}
Rd7 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd7b7]} 8. Rbd1 Qc6 9. Rxd7+ Qxd7 10. Rxe6+ $16 {[%csl
Ra7,Rb7][%cal Gf3b7] The two black queenside pawns are going to fall. This,
together with the lack of coordination of pieces and the exposed king,
guarantees White's advantage.}) (1... exd5 2. Re1+ Be7 3. Bg5 f6 4. Be3 $16 {
[%csl Rd5,Re8][%cal Gb3g8]}) 2. f4 $1 {Playing energetically!.} e4 3. f5 {
[%cal Gc1f4,Gf5f6]} Qf6 4. Ba4+ Kd8 5. d6 $1 {[%csl Rd8] An excellent pawn
sacrifice to highlight the terrible location of the black king.} Nxa4 6. Qxa4
Bxd6 7. Be3 $16 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gd1d6,Ge3d4]} *

