{Black has exchanged a minor piece and has the white isolated pawn well
blocked. What is the best continuation for White? Justify with variations.} 1.
Bg5 $3 {An unexpected and spectacular bishop sacrifice, highlighting the lack
of development of the second player.} Qxg5 ({Big mistakes are:} 1... f6 $2 2.
Qh5+ $18) (1... Be7 $2 2. Bxe7 Qxe7 3. Nxd5 exd5 4. Ng6 $18) 2. Nxd5 exd5 3.
Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c8] The most accurate continuation, posing immediate threats on
the eighth rank. Despite the extra piece, Black has no solution and must
minimize the damage.} Nd7 (3... Qd8 4. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3f7]} Ra7 ({
No solution is} 4... f6 5. Rfe1 fxe5 (5... Be7 6. Qh5+ g6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. Qxh8+
Kd7 9. Qh3+ $18 {The black position is impossible to defend.}) 6. Qh5+ g6 7.
Qxe5+ $18) 5. Rfe1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Ge5f7]} Bb4 6. Nxf7+ Bxe1 7. Nxd8 $18 {
Winning.}) (3... Qf5 {[%cal Gf5f3,Gf5c8]} 4. Re1 {[%cal Ge5g6,Ge5c6]} Be7 5.
Rc7 {[%csl Re7]} O-O 6. Rxe7 {[%csl Rd5] Black's queenside pieces have large
problems developing.} Qc8 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 7. Rxf7 $1 {White gives no respite
and capitalizes on his advantage.} Rxf7 8. Nxf7 Nc6 (8... Kxf7 $2 9. Qh5+ Kf8
10. Qf3+ Kg8 11. Qxd5+ $18) 9. Qh5 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gh5d5,Gf7g5,Gf7e5]}) 4.
Re1 Be7 5. Nc6 O-O 6. Nxe7+ Kh8 7. g3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge7d5,Gh2h4]} Nf6 8. Re5
Qg4 9. Qxg4 Nxg4 10. Rxd5 {With a clear extra pawn in the endgame.} *

